Porter’s Five Forces

Competitive Rivalry

V.High (http://eds.a.ebscohost.com.ezproxy.wit.ie:2048/eds/pdfviewer/pdfviewer?vid=12&sid=f16ba6c8-e45d-4c36-953a-390f6bb53e6a%40sdc-v-sessmgr05) IBM SWOT analysis from market line
(http://eds.a.ebscohost.com.ezproxy.wit.ie:2048/eds/pdfviewer/pdfviewer?vid=15&sid=f16ba6c8-e45d-4c36-953a-390f6bb53e6a%40sdc-v-sessmgr05) Cisco SWOT analysis from market line

“The company operates in a highly competitive environment, where its competitors vary by industry segment, and range from large multinational enterprises to smaller, more narrowly focused entities. In order to maintain leadership, IBM must continue to invest, innovate and integrate” From the IBM SWOT ^^

“The company faces intense competition in the networking and communications equipment markets. These markets are characterized by rapid change, converging technologies, and a migration to networking and communications solutions that offer relative advantages. Cisco competes with several vendors in each product category. The company's major competitors include Alcatel-Lucent; Amazon Web Services; Arista Networks; ARRIS Group; Avaya; Blue Jeans Networks; Brocade Communications; Check Point Software Technologies; Citrix Systems; Dell; LM Ericsson; Extreme Networks; F5 Networks; FireEye; Fortinet; HP; Huawei Technologies; IBM; Juniper Networks; Microsoft; Motorola Solutions; Palo Alto Networks; Polycom; Riverbed Technology; Ruckus Wireless; Symantec; Ubiquiti Networks; and VMware; among others.” From the Cisco SWOT


Threat of New Entry
Medium, due to intense competitive rivalry however increasing instances of hacking may create opportunities for newer companies to provide a security service despite the niche formed in IT security such as Amazon and Facebook.

Supplier Power
High due to increased instances of hacking.

Buyer power
High due to competitive rivalry. 

Threat of Substitutes
 Low, example, Gmail’s phishing detection, not the product but comes with the product as a function.




